@startuml
skinparam linetype ortho

title Programming by Geometry: The Life of a Braid

[*] --> Initialization : Human Prompt

state "Phase 1: Grounding (Data -> Coordinate)" as Initialization {
  state "Morton Encoding" as Morton
  state "Extract GF(257) Phase" as Phase
  
  Morton : X = Byte Value
  Morton : Y = Sequence Index
  Phase : Map to Mono-Type (The Value)
  
  Morton -> Phase
}

note right of Initialization
  <b>The Programmer's Input</b>
  We don't give the system "code". 
  We give it a Boundary Value (a start 
  coordinate and a target Anchor Phase).
end note

state "Phase 2: The Logic Engine (Layer 2)" as Engine {
  
  state "Apply Momentum (The Opcode)" as Rotate {
    state "Affine Rotation" as Affine
    Affine : State = a(State) + b (mod 257)
    Affine : Generative / Non-Destructive
  }
  
  state "Wavefront Measurement" as Measurement <<choice>>
  
  state "Constructive Interference" as Resonance {
    state "Phase-Lock" as Lock
    Lock : High Saturation / Low Residue
    Lock : The Rotation becomes the Pointer
  }
  
  state "Destructive Interference" as Noise {
    state "Entropy Sink" as Prune
    Prune : Path mathematically dies
  }
  
  Rotate --> Measurement : XOR Projected Phase\nAgainst Stored LSM Paths
  Measurement --> Resonance : [Match]
  Measurement --> Noise :[Mismatch / High Entropy]
}

note top of Rotate
  <b>Rotation IS Logic</b>
  This is the "Execution". The engine 
  spins the Fermat cube to point toward 
  the next logical concept.
end note

note bottom of Measurement
  <b>XOR IS Measurement</b>
  We do NOT store the XOR. We only use 
  XOR to check if our rotated Value hit 
  a valid physical coordinate in the LSM.
end note

state "Phase 3: The Halt Evaluator" as HaltCheck <<choice>>

state "Phase 4: Projection (Coordinate -> Data)" as Output {
  state "O(1) Spatial Lookup" as Lookup
  state "Un-Morton" as Decode
  
  Lookup : Retrieve X from LSM
  Decode : Convert X back to Byte
  Lookup -> Decode
}

note bottom of Output
  <b>Translation for Puny Humans</b>
  The system drops out of Layer 2 (Math)
  back into Layer 1 (Bytes/Pixels) to 
  return the answer.
end note

Initialization --> Rotate : Inject Initial Phase

Resonance --> HaltCheck
Noise --> [*] : Branch Pruned

HaltCheck --> Rotate : [Bit 257 == 0]\nAND\n[Not Saturated]\n(Loop / Advance)
HaltCheck --> Output :[Bit 257 == 1]\nOR\n[Maximum Saturation]\n(Fixed Point Reached)

Output --> [*] : Return Final Bytes

@enduml

